President Biden has declared a state of emergency in Illinois due to severe storms, straight-line winds, and tornadoes that occurred on December 10, 2021. This declaration allows the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) to coordinate disaster relief efforts and provide assistance to the affected counties. FEMA is authorized to mobilize equipment and resources to alleviate the impact of the emergency, with 75 percent of funding coming from the federal government. Brian F. Schiller has been named as the Federal Coordinating Officer for recovery operations in the affected areas. For more information, the media can contact the FEMA News Desk.